# Exercise 5 – Task Management System

## Objective

The objective of this exercise is to understand the implementation of a Singly Linked List by creating a Task Management System. The system performs operations such as adding, searching, traversing, and deleting tasks.

## Understanding Linked Lists

A linked list is a linear data structure in which each element is stored in a separate node. Each node contains data and a reference (pointer) to the next node. Unlike arrays, linked lists do not require contiguous memory allocation.

### Types of Linked Lists

### 1. Singly Linked List

* Each node contains data and one pointer to the next node.
* Traversal is possible only in the forward direction.
* Requires less memory compared to a doubly linked list.

### 2. Doubly Linked List

* Each node contains data, a pointer to the next node, and a pointer to the previous node.
* Supports traversal in both forward and backward directions.
* Requires more memory because each node stores two pointers.

## Operations Performed

* Add Task
* Search Task
* Traverse Task List
* Delete Task

## Time Complexity Analysis

| Operation | Time Complexity |
| --------- | --------------- |
| Add       | O(n)            |
| Search    | O(n)            |
| Traverse  | O(n)            |
| Delete    | O(n)            |

## Advantages of Linked Lists over Arrays

* Dynamic size; memory is allocated as needed.
* Easy insertion and deletion without shifting elements.
* Better memory utilization for applications with changing data.
* Suitable for implementing stacks, queues, and other dynamic data structures.

